"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 26–28 (fill)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1chronicles-26-28-fill.py

Fills 84 missing verses (ch26 except v12; ch27 except v23; ch28 except v11).
Context layer = historical, geographic, social, administrative background.

Key decisions:
- Ch26: Levitical gatekeepers and treasury officials — temple security and finance
- Ch27: Monthly military rotation (288,000 total), tribal officers, agricultural stewards,
  royal advisors — administrative state comparable to contemporary Near Eastern kingdoms
- Ch28: David's final assembly, divine prohibition, and delivery of temple architectural plans
- The 12-month military division system is unique to Chronicles with no direct parallel
  in Samuel; comparable systems appear in Assyrian and Egyptian administrative texts
- v27:23-24 (census omission) connects to the Davidic census sin of ch21
- v28:11-19 describes a written divine plan analogous to Mosaic tabernacle blueprints
"""

import json, os

def load_comm(layer, book):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    if os.path.exists(path):
        with open(path) as f:
            return json.load(f)
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(path), exist_ok=True)
    with open(path, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(data, f, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None)
    print(f'wrote {path}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

CHRONICLES = {
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>The gatekeeper (šōʿēr) institution was one of the most important elements of ancient temple administration. Gatekeepers controlled access to the sacred precincts, maintained temple security, received offerings, and managed the movement of personnel and materials. Ancient Near Eastern temples employed similar door-wardens whose records survive from Egypt (where temple gatekeepers policed against ritual impurity) and Mesopotamia (where gate-wardens managed temple storerooms). The Korahites (descended from Korah of the Levites) had a distinctive role in temple security; despite Korah&rsquo;s rebellion (Num 16), his descendants continued in Levitical service (Num 26:11).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Meshelemiah&rsquo;s seven sons with birth-order rankings reflect the hereditary structure of gatekeeper families: gate assignments passed from father to son, with birth-order determining seniority within the family unit. The assignment of temple roles by lineage created stable multi-generational guilds whose institutional memory and physical familiarity with the sanctuary provided continuity across royal reigns and political changes.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Elam, Jehohanan, and Elioenai (the fifth through seventh sons) fill out Meshelemiah&rsquo;s household roster. The seven-son list for Meshelemiah parallels the musical family lists of ch15, where three musical guilds each head large hereditary teams. The gatekeeper guilds operated on a similar hereditary-guild model: the chief gatekeeper&rsquo;s family produced the senior officers while other Levitical families supplied the rank-and-file guards.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Obed-edom&rsquo;s eight sons are explicitly connected to the divine blessing he received while hosting the ark (13:13&ndash;14): &ldquo;God had blessed Obed-edom.&rdquo; The large household (eight sons plus extended family) is presented as the concrete evidence of the blessing. Ancient readers understood large families as YHWH&rsquo;s favour; Obed-edom&rsquo;s transition from ark-host to gatekeeper represents the integration of his family into the permanent temple service structure.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Peulthai the eighth son (&ldquo;recompense of YHWH&rdquo;) closes Obed-edom&rsquo;s list with the theological explanation for the family&rsquo;s size: divine blessing. The enumeration of eight sons (vs. seven for Meshelemiah) marks Obed-edom&rsquo;s family as exceptionally favoured. In the temple service roster, a larger hereditary unit meant greater representation in the rotation and potentially more prestigious gate assignments.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Shemaiah&rsquo;s sons are described as &ldquo;men of outstanding ability who exercised leadership in their father&rsquo;s household.&rdquo; The phrase reflects the ancient Near Eastern concept of hereditary administrative competence: sons of officials were expected to surpass their fathers through demonstrated capability, not merely inherit positions. Egyptian and Akkadian wisdom texts frequently address the training of sons to assume their fathers&rsquo; administrative roles.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Shemaiah&rsquo;s sons (Othni, Rephael, Obed, Elzabad) plus kinsmen Elihu and Semachiah form a six-person leadership team for Obed-edom&rsquo;s sub-clan. The dual designation &ldquo;of ability&rdquo; (ʾanšê ḥayil) for the kinsmen identifies them as qualified professionals, not merely hereditary placeholders. The Chronicler&rsquo;s emphasis on merit alongside heredity reflects the administrative pragmatism of the Persian-period temple state, where competent personnel were needed for the complex operation of the Second Temple.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The total of 62 men for Obed-edom&rsquo;s gatekeeper division makes it one of the largest single-family units in the temple administration. For comparison, the entire returnee community of Zerubbabel&rsquo;s period numbered only about 50,000 (Ezra 2:64&ndash;65). A gatekeeper family of 62 adult males would have constituted a significant portion of the post-exilic Jerusalem community, reflecting both the blessing-tradition attached to Obed-edom and the importance of adequate temple security staffing.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Meshelemiah&rsquo;s 18-man total is smaller than Obed-edom&rsquo;s 62, suggesting different generations of the genealogical record or different source traditions. The Korahite-Merarite division of gatekeeper responsibility (v19) likely reflected historical guild boundaries rather than purely theological distinctions: the two guilds may have originated from different periods of the temple security system&rsquo;s development, with the Korahites being older and the Merarites added later.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Hosah&rsquo;s appointment of Simri as head despite his non-firstborn status is an interesting administrative decision. The father overrides birth-order preference (&ldquo;his father had appointed him head&rdquo;) on the basis of demonstrated competence or personal favour. This parallels Jacob&rsquo;s preferential treatment of Joseph (Gen 37) and several other biblical instances where the firstborn principle was set aside for the more capable or divinely-chosen son. In temple administration, competence in managing security personnel presumably outweighed strict birth order.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The total of 13 men for Hosah&rsquo;s Merarite division makes it the smallest of the three gatekeeper families. The three families together (Meshelemiah 18, Hosah 13, Obed-edom 62) provide 93 men for the four-gate rotation described in vv14&ndash;18. With four gates each staffed by different numbers per day (east 6, north 4, south 4, storehouse 2 = 16 per day, plus the west gate guards), the 93-man pool supported a continuous rotation through the week.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The lottery system (gôrāl) for gate assignments ensured that no family gained permanent control over the most prestigious gate (the east, facing YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling place) while disadvantaging others. Lottery assignment was a standard ancient Near Eastern mechanism for dividing administrative responsibilities; it appears in the Ugaritic administrative texts (where lots were cast for priestly rotation) and is used throughout Chronicles for Levitical assignments (24:7, 31; 25:8&ndash;9). The principle &ldquo;small and great alike&rdquo; ensured democratic access to all positions regardless of family size.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The east gate (facing the rising sun and the direction of YHWH&rsquo;s glory, Ezek 43:1&ndash;4) was the most theologically significant entrance. Shelemiah (= Meshelemiah, a name variant) receiving it by lot underscores that the assignment was divinely directed through the lottery rather than politically arranged. Zechariah, described as &ldquo;a wise counselor&rdquo; (yōʿēṣ biśkāl), receives the north gate &mdash; the characterization of a gatekeeper as a counselor suggests these officers had advisory as well as security functions.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The south gate and the storehouse (ʾāsuppîm) were assigned to Obed-edom and his sons. The storehouse (translated &ldquo;Asuppim&rdquo; in older versions) was a specific temple facility, probably the area where offerings and dedicated gifts were collected and stored. Obed-edom&rsquo;s family assignment to the storehouse is logical given that his line also provided treasury oversight (v15 connects with v24&ndash;28): the family that had hosted the ark was now the family guarding the temple&rsquo;s material resources.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Shallecheth Gate (šaʿar šalleḵet, &ldquo;the throwing-out gate&rdquo; or &ldquo;gate of the falling leaves&rdquo;) on the west side was likely the gate through which refuse and waste were removed from the temple complex. It appears only here in the Hebrew Bible. The &ldquo;ascending road&rdquo; (mesillāh) leading to the west gate may be the ramp or causeway connecting the temple mount to the city below, making this a commercially significant entry point for materials coming up from the lower city.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The daily guard rosters (east: 6; north: 4; south: 4; storehouse: 2 and 2) reflect a tiered security system based on the relative importance and traffic of each gate. The east gate&rsquo;s six guards represent the highest-security watch; the storehouse&rsquo;s four guards (2 at each side) focus on protecting the temple treasury. This kind of differential staffing is attested in Near Eastern administrative records: Egyptian temple records from Karnak specify different guard contingents for different access points based on their strategic importance.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Parbar (parbār) is a technical architectural term of uncertain meaning, appearing only here and in 2 Kgs 23:11. It likely refers to a western courtyard or annex of the temple precinct. Some scholars connect the term to the Persian word for a side-room (parvāra) or to an architectural feature known from the Mishnah (Tractate Middot) which describes a structure on the western side of the temple mount. The four-guard assignment for the Parbar roadway and two for Parbar itself suggests a complex multi-point access system on the western approach.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The summary note that the gatekeeper divisions came from &ldquo;the Korahite and Merarite lines&rdquo; distinguishes the temple security guilds from the musical guilds (which involved all three Levitical families: Kohath/Heman, Gershon/Asaph, Merari/Ethan). The Korahite specialization in gate-keeping may reflect their ancient association with the tabernacle entrance and the memory of Korah&rsquo;s attempted priestly usurpation (Num 16): the family compensated for that ancestral failure by becoming expert guardians against unauthorized access to the holy space.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ahijah (or reading with LXX/Syriac: &ldquo;their fellow Levites&rdquo; rather than a personal name) overseeing the treasuries introduces the temple finance administration. The dual treasury system &mdash; &ldquo;treasuries of God&rsquo;s house&rdquo; (ongoing temple operational funds) and &ldquo;treasuries of dedicated gifts&rdquo; (consecrated spoils and donations) &mdash; mirrors the administrative structure of major ancient Near Eastern temples. Mesopotamian temples maintained separate accounts for the god&rsquo;s own revenues and for donations from kings and worshippers.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Gershonite Ladan (= Libni, 6:17) line provides the treasury supervisors. The Gershonites&rsquo; assignment to financial oversight rather than gate-keeping reflects the institutional diversification of Levitical roles as the temple establishment grew more complex. The Chronicler&rsquo;s preservation of these treasury assignments suggests the post-exilic Second Temple maintained a comparable administrative division, with different Levitical families responsible for physical security (gatekeepers), financial management (treasury supervisors), and musical worship (singers).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Zetham and Joel, sons of Jehiel, oversaw the LORD&rsquo;s house treasuries. The Jehielite sub-clan of the Gershonites appears in 23:8 as among the chiefs of Ladan&rsquo;s line. Financial oversight of the temple treasury was a position of extraordinary trust and responsibility; the selection of specific named individuals for this role (rather than a lottery assignment) reflects the personal accountability required for custodians of the community&rsquo;s most valuable assets.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The four Kohathite sub-clans (Amramites, Izharites, Hebronites, Uzzielites) all contribute to the administrative apparatus. These are the same four sub-clans whose transport assignments were specified in Numbers 3&ndash;4. The Mosaic-era organization by clan thus persists from the wilderness period through David&rsquo;s administrative reorganization into the Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic vision: the four Kohathite divisions represent a structural continuity across a thousand years of Israelite cultic history.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Shebuel son of Gershom son of Moses as &ldquo;chief official over the treasuries&rdquo; is a striking appointment: Moses&rsquo; grandson through his firstborn son Gershom becomes the head of the temple&rsquo;s financial administration. This places the Mosaic bloodline in the highest administrative position below the Aaronic priests, a deliberate honour to the Lawgiver&rsquo;s family that compensated for the fact that Mosaic descendants held no priestly functions (those belonging exclusively to Aaron&rsquo;s line). The appointment validated Moses&rsquo; family&rsquo;s importance without challenging the Aaronic priesthood.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The parallel Mosaic line through Eliezer (Moses&rsquo; second son, Exod 18:4) produces Shelomith after five intervening generations. The five-generation gap between Moses and David&rsquo;s era presents a chronological problem (the period should require more generations), suggesting either compressed genealogy or a different Eliezer/Shelomith pair. The parallel to Shebuel through Gershom establishes both Mosaic branches as participants in the Davidic temple administration, making the appointment politically inclusive of both sons&rsquo; traditions.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Shelomith and his relatives oversee the dedicated gifts (qŏḏāšîm) consecrated by David, family heads, military commanders, and other officers. The dedicated gifts (ḥerem-type consecrations from battle spoil) were a major source of temple funding in the ancient world. Mesopotamian inscriptions record royal temples receiving gold, silver, and luxury goods from conquered peoples&rsquo; treasuries; Israelite dedicated-gift traditions (like the Midianite spoils in Num 31:50&ndash;54) provided a similar endowment mechanism for the sanctuary.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The explanation that battle spoils (&ldquo;from the wars and the plunder&rdquo;) were dedicated to sustain and repair the temple connects military success to cultic maintenance. In the ancient world, victorious kings routinely dedicated a portion of war-spoils to their patron deity&rsquo;s temple; this practice appears in Mesopotamian royal inscriptions, Ugaritic texts, and the Mesha Stele (where the Moabite king Mesha dedicates captured vessels to Chemosh). The Chronicler validates this practice as part of David&rsquo;s temple-preparation legacy.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Samuel, Saul, Abner, and Joab are listed as dedicators of gifts that are now in Shelomith&rsquo;s custody. This roster spans from the last judge (Samuel) through Israel&rsquo;s first king (Saul) and his military commander (Abner) to David&rsquo;s general (Joab) &mdash; covering the entire transition period from judges to the Davidic monarchy. The inclusion of Saul and Abner (both from the rival dynasty and both ultimately defeated) in the treasury dedication list signals that all legitimate leaders of Israel contributed to the eventual temple, regardless of their political allegiance.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Izharite Chenaniah and his sons administered &ldquo;external affairs&rdquo; (hammᵉlāʾḵāh haḥîṣônāh) as officials and judges. This distinction between internal temple affairs and external administrative responsibilities reflects the dual role of the Levites in the Chronicler&rsquo;s vision: they served both the sanctuary and the broader civil administration of the state. In the Persian period, the Levitical administrative network would have extended throughout Judah&rsquo;s villages and towns, providing judicial and financial oversight at the local level.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The Hebronite Hashabiah with 1,700 men overseeing the western half of the Jordan (Cisjordan) represents a large regional administrative corps. The assignment of Levites to regional governance &mdash; west of Jordan for Hashabiah, east of Jordan (Gilead and Bashan) for Jerijah (v31&ndash;32) &mdash; mirrors the administrative geography of David&rsquo;s kingdom. The Levitical administrative system functioned as the state civil service, providing officials who were accountable to both the king and the temple rather than to tribal chiefs.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Jerijah as chief of the Hebronite genealogical register is found &ldquo;in the fortieth year of David&rsquo;s reign.&rdquo; This specific date places the administrative reorganization in David&rsquo;s last year (1 Kgs 2:11: David reigned 40 years). The genealogical search (&ldquo;organized by genealogies of their ancestral houses&rdquo;) at this late date reflects the Davidic administration&rsquo;s effort to document Levitical family affiliations before the succession of Solomon, ensuring institutional continuity across the dynastic transition.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The 2,700 Hebronite officials appointed over the Reubenites, Gadites, and Manassites on the east of the Jordan (Gilead and Bashan) represent the Transjordanian administrative complement. These eastern territories were strategically important border zones; Reuben and Gad occupied the land that had historically been Moabite and Ammonite territory, requiring ongoing administrative oversight to maintain Israelite control. The appointment of Levites &mdash; with no tribal land-stake in the east &mdash; as regional administrators ensured loyalty to the central government rather than local tribal interests.</p>"
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>The twelve-division monthly military rotation system described in ch27 has no direct parallel in Samuel or Kings but is comparable to administrative systems attested in ancient Near Eastern kingdoms. The Assyrian ḫalṣu system used regional military districts supplying rotation troops to the central army; the Egyptian administrative system divided the country into divisions supplying labor and military contingents by rotation. David&rsquo;s system of 24,000 men per month (288,000 total across twelve rotations) would have created a professional standing army whose members served one month per year while maintaining their agricultural livelihoods for the other eleven months.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jashobeam son of Zabdiel commanded the first division for the first month. Jashobeam is identified in 11:11 as the chief of David&rsquo;s &ldquo;three&rdquo; (the elite warrior group); his placement as the senior commander of the first monthly division is consistent with his status as the kingdom&rsquo;s preeminent warrior. The command of the first month carried symbolic primacy: the first division set the standard for the year&rsquo;s military readiness.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jashobeam&rsquo;s connection to Perez (Judah&rsquo;s line through Tamar) marks the first division as under Davidic tribal command. The &ldquo;senior commander for the first month&rdquo; designation (rōʾš kol-haśśārîm laḥōḏeš hārīʾšôn) suggests Jashobeam held not just divisional command but a supervisory role over all twelve monthly commanders, consistent with his position as David&rsquo;s chief warrior.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Dodai the Ahohite commanded the second month; Mikloth served as his officer. Dodai appears in 11:12 as the second of the three elite warriors (Eleazar son of Dodai in MT; the name reflects the same military family). The Ahohites were a Benjaminite sub-clan (8:4), representing the first Benjaminite commander in the rotation &mdash; appropriate for Israel&rsquo;s second tribe in the historical narrative.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Benaiah son of Jehoiada the priest commanded the third month. Benaiah was David&rsquo;s chief of the Cherethites and Pelethites (the royal bodyguard composed of foreign mercenaries, 2 Sam 8:18; 20:23) and one of the thirty elite warriors. His description as &ldquo;the priest&rdquo; for Jehoiada indicates his father held the Aaronic priesthood, making Benaiah unusual: a military commander of priestly descent. Benaiah&rsquo;s later role in executing David&rsquo;s rivals and securing Solomon&rsquo;s throne (1 Kgs 2:25, 34) reflects his trusted insider status.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The note that Benaiah was &ldquo;a mighty man among the thirty and above the thirty&rdquo; establishes his rank within David&rsquo;s warrior hierarchy (the full list appears in ch11:10&ndash;47). His son Ammizabad commanded in his place, suggesting Benaiah&rsquo;s primary duties (royal bodyguard, later military commander under Solomon) prevented personal monthly divisional service. The succession of a son within a single year&rsquo;s rotation illustrates the hereditary aspects of military command positions.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Asahel brother of Joab commanded the fourth month; his son Zebadiah succeeded him. Asahel was killed by Abner (2 Sam 2:23) early in David&rsquo;s career, so Zebadiah&rsquo;s actual command is the operative appointment. This retrospective listing of Asahel as the division&rsquo;s nominal founder may reflect the Chronicler&rsquo;s desire to honour the original appointment while recording the practical succession. Honoring a fallen hero by maintaining his name in the rotation was a form of institutional memory-keeping.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Shamhuth the Izrahite commanded the fifth month. The Izrahite designation (from Zerah of Judah, 2:6) marks this as another Judahite commander. The fifth-month command with 24,000 men would have covered the beginning of the harvest season (Sivan/Tammuz, May&ndash;June), when agricultural labor competed with military service; the rotation system&rsquo;s genius was that 24,000 men served in any given month while the remaining 264,000 were available for agricultural and economic production.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ira son of Ikkesh the Tekoite commanded the sixth month. Ira appears in 11:28 among the thirty heroes, connecting the monthly division commanders to David&rsquo;s personal warrior band. Tekoa (modern Khirbet Teku&rsquo;a) was a Judahite town in the highlands south of Bethlehem, the hometown of the prophet Amos. Its warriors were known for their familiarity with the Judean wilderness terrain &mdash; valuable knowledge for both defense and desert campaigns.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Helez the Pelonite from Ephraim commanded the seventh month. The inclusion of an Ephraimite commander marks the rotation system&rsquo;s all-Israel character: commanders came from multiple tribes, not exclusively from Judah or Benjamin. Helez appears in 11:27 as a hero; his Pelonite designation is uncertain (LXX reads &ldquo;Paltite,&rdquo; connecting him to Beth-pelet in the Negev). The seventh month (Tishri) was Israel&rsquo;s most sacred cultic month (New Year, Day of Atonement, Sukkot), making the military rotation for this month symbolically important.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Sibbecai the Hushathite of the Zerahite line commanded the eighth month. Sibbecai appears in 20:4 as the warrior who killed the Philistine giant Sippai (also called Saph in 2 Sam 21:18). Hushah was a Judahite town (4:4); the Zerahite affiliation places him in Judah&rsquo;s Zerah sub-clan. The Hushathites may have been a hereditary military family specializing in giant-combat, given Sibbecai&rsquo;s specific noted achievement against Sippai.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Abiezer the Anetothite from Benjamin commanded the ninth month. Anathoth (Jeremiah&rsquo;s home, Jer 1:1) was a Benjaminite Levitical city with a notable warrior tradition; its citizens appear both in the Levitical service lists and in the military rosters of ch11. The ninth month (Kislev, November&ndash;December) was the beginning of the rainy season in Canaan, limiting offensive operations but requiring the maintenance of defensive readiness against the same seasonal constraints facing potential enemies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Maharai the Netophathite of the Zerahite line commanded the tenth month. Netophah (2:54; Ezra 2:22) was a Judahite town near Bethlehem, producing several of David&rsquo;s elite warriors (Maharai and Heldai in v15 are both Netophathite). The concentration of warriors from a single small town reflects the ancient phenomenon of martial culture in specific localities: some towns developed reputations as warrior communities through generations of military service and training.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Benaiah the Pirathonite from Ephraim commanded the eleventh month. Pirathon (modern Farata, near Shechem) was an Ephraimite town known from the judge Abdon (Judg 12:13&ndash;15). Two different Benaiahs appear in the twelve-division roster (this Ephraimite and the priestly son of Jehoiada in v5), illustrating the common name&rsquo;s distribution across tribes and social classes in this period.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Heldai the Netophathite descended from Othniel commanded the twelfth month. Othniel was the first judge of Israel (Judg 3:9&ndash;11) and a Calebite hero; claiming descent from Othniel gave a warrior a prestige genealogy connecting to Israel&rsquo;s judicial founding tradition. Heldai appears in Zech 6:10 as one of the returnees from Babylon who brought gold and silver for a crown, connecting the Davidic warrior tradition to the post-exilic restoration community.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The tribal officer list (vv16&ndash;22) assigns a nāśîʾ (prince, officer) to each tribe to manage tribal affairs within David&rsquo;s administrative state. Reuben&rsquo;s officer Eliezer son of Zichri, and Simeon&rsquo;s Shephatiah son of Maacah, represent the eastern and southern periphery tribes with the smallest populations and most distant territories. The appointment of tribal officers complemented the monthly division commanders: the former managed tribal civilian affairs while the latter commanded military service.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The inclusion of &ldquo;the Levites&rdquo; and &ldquo;the Aaronites&rdquo; as separate administrative units alongside the secular tribes reflects the dual structure of the Davidic state: a tribal civil system and a Levitical-priestly religious system operating in parallel. Hashabiah son of Kemuel (a Levite) and Zadok (the high priest) represent these parallel tracks. Zadok&rsquo;s designation as officer for &ldquo;the Aaronites&rdquo; marks the Aaronic priesthood as a distinct administrative category requiring its own representative to the king.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Elihu &ldquo;one of David&rsquo;s brothers&rdquo; as Judah&rsquo;s tribal officer reflects the political logic of the dominant tribe: David&rsquo;s own family managed Judah&rsquo;s tribal affairs, keeping the core of the kingdom within the royal household. The designation &ldquo;of David&rsquo;s brothers&rdquo; (mēʾaḥê ḏāwîḏ) does not mean a full brother (all David&rsquo;s brothers are named in 2:13&ndash;16) but a close kinsman. Issachar&rsquo;s officer Omri son of Michael has an Israelite name (Michael = &ldquo;who is like God&rdquo;) and a pagan-origin name (Omri = Babylonian ʿumri, possibly meaning &ldquo;lifetime&rdquo;), illustrating the name mixing of the early monarchy.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Zebulun&rsquo;s Ishmaiah son of Obadiah and Naphtali&rsquo;s Jerimoth son of Azriel represent the northern Galilean tribes. Zebulun occupied the lower Galilee between Issachar and the Phoenician coast; Naphtali held the upper Galilee and the Jordan valley north of the Sea of Galilee. Both tribal territories bordered Phoenicia and Aram, giving their tribal officers a diplomatic as well as administrative function in managing the northern frontier.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Hoshea son of Azaziah for Ephraim and Joel son of Pedaiah for western Manasseh represent the central highland tribes. Ephraim and Manasseh together constituted the most populous region of the kingdom; their tribal officers managed the agricultural heartland of Israel. The separate appointments for western Manasseh (v20) and Gilead/Transjordanian Manasseh (v21) reflect the geographical reality that the two halves of Manasseh were separated by the Jordan valley and functioned as distinct administrative units.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Iddo son of Zechariah for Transjordanian Manasseh (Gilead) and Jaasiel son of Abner for Benjamin. The appointment of Abner&rsquo;s son as Benjaminite officer is significant: Abner was Saul&rsquo;s military commander who initially opposed David (2 Sam 2&ndash;3) and was killed by Joab (2 Sam 3:27). David&rsquo;s appointment of Abner&rsquo;s son as a tribal officer signals the reconciliation of Benjaminite loyalties to the Davidic crown &mdash; a politically shrewd inclusion of the former rival dynasty&rsquo;s family in the new administrative structure.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Dan&rsquo;s officer Azareel son of Jeroham is the only time Dan appears in 1 Chronicles&rsquo; main narrative (the tribe is absent from the genealogies of ch2&ndash;9). The inclusion here but not in the genealogical section may reflect the Chronicler&rsquo;s use of a different source for administrative lists: the tribal officer roster preserved Dan while the genealogical sources (possibly compiled after Dan&rsquo;s territory was overrun by Assyria in 733 BCE) omitted it. The summary note &ldquo;these were the leaders of the tribes of Israel&rdquo; encompasses all twelve tribes.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The incomplete census (David ordered but Joab did not finish it) references the census disaster of ch21, where YHWH sent plague on Israel in response to David&rsquo;s count. The reason given here &mdash; &ldquo;wrath came upon Israel because of it&rdquo; &mdash; confirms the ch21 narrative. The note that &ldquo;the number was not entered in the official register of King David&rdquo; explains why no census total for this particular count appears: the unfinished, cursed count was administratively suppressed. This verse explains the gap in David&rsquo;s records that modern interpreters might notice.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Azmaveth son of Adiel managed the royal storehouses (ʾōṣᵃrôt hammelek) in Jerusalem; Jonathan son of Uzziah managed the field storehouses in the provinces. The dual treasury system &mdash; central stores in Jerusalem and distributed regional granaries &mdash; mirrors the administrative geography of ancient Near Eastern kingdoms. Assyrian and Egyptian records describe both palace central stores and provincial granaries drawing from agricultural regions; the Solomonic administrative district system (1 Kgs 4:7&ndash;19) built on this Davidic foundation.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Ezri son of Chelub oversaw the agricultural laborers who worked the royal fields (lᵃʿōḇᵉḏê hāʾᵃḏāmāh). The royal agricultural estate was a standard feature of ancient Near Eastern kingdoms; the Gezer Agricultural Calendar (ca. 925 BCE, the oldest known Hebrew inscription) lists the agricultural cycle that royal estate workers managed. Royal estates in Canaan produced the grain, oil, and wine needed to feed the administrative apparatus and provide the surplus for trade and military provisioning.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Shimei the Ramathite for vineyards and Zabdi the Shiphmite for wine production managed Israel&rsquo;s most economically significant agricultural sectors. Wine was the primary luxury agricultural export of the Levantine region: Phoenician and Israelite wines were traded throughout the Mediterranean world from the Bronze Age onward. Dedicated managers for the vine-growing (Shimei) and wine-cellar (Zabdi) functions indicate the economic importance of the royal wine operation, which served both consumption and diplomatic-tribute purposes.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Baalhanan the Gederite for olive trees and sycamore figs in the Shephelah (the foothill zone between the highlands and the Philistine plain) managed Israel&rsquo;s other major agricultural export. Olive oil from the Shephelah was a major trade commodity; archaeological evidence from Tel Miqne (Ekron) shows large-scale olive-oil production at a Philistine city immediately adjacent to this region. Joash&rsquo;s management of the oil stores reflects the specialized knowledge required for large-scale oil production and storage.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Shitrai the Sharonite and Shaphat son of Adlai managed the royal cattle herds in the Sharon plain and the valleys. The Sharon plain (the coastal strip north of Jaffa) was known for its pastureland (Isa 35:2; 65:10); the valleys (ʿᵃmāqîm) were the lowland grazing areas of the Jezreel and Jordan valleys. Large-scale cattle management at royal estates is attested in ancient Near Eastern records; the scale implied here (separate managers for different herding regions) suggests thousands of animals in the royal herds.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Obil the Ishmaelite managed the camels; Jehdeiah the Meronothite managed the donkeys. The appointment of an Ishmaelite for camel management is fitting: Ishmael&rsquo;s descendants were the traditional camel-herders and caravan operators of the Arabian peninsula and Negev (Gen 37:25; Judg 8:24&ndash;26). The use of ethnic specialists for different livestock categories reflects the ancient practice of assigning management roles based on traditional expertise. Camels, as long-distance transport animals, required different husbandry knowledge than the pack donkeys used for local transport.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Jaziz the Hagerite managed the royal flocks. The Hagerites (descendants of Hagar? Or an Arabian tribe?) appear in Ps 83:6 as enemies of Israel; their appearance here as royal administrators reflects the Davidic kingdom&rsquo;s incorporation of neighboring peoples into its administrative service. The closing formula (&ldquo;these were all the stewards of David&rsquo;s royal holdings&rdquo;) indicates this list was a formal administrative register &mdash; a royal property inventory that documented the kingdom&rsquo;s agricultural-pastoral assets under named custodians.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Jonathan David&rsquo;s uncle (dôḏ, a general word for male relative as well as specific uncle) served as royal counselor and scribe (sōpēr). The combination of counselor and scribe functions reflects the ancient Near Eastern scribal-advisory role: trained scribes in Egypt, Babylon, and Assyria served as the primary advisors to rulers because they could read documents, draft correspondence, and summarize information from written records. Jonathan&rsquo;s literacy and discretion (&ldquo;discerning&rdquo;) made him the equivalent of a modern chief-of-staff.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Ahithophel and Hushai the Archite occupied the two most senior advisory roles. Ahithophel&rsquo;s counsel was proverbially reliable (&ldquo;as if one consulted the oracle of God,&rdquo; 2 Sam 16:23); his defection to Absalom and subsequent suicide after his advice was rejected (2 Sam 17:23) made him the tragic exemplar of royal advisor failure. Hushai&rsquo;s appointment as &ldquo;the king&rsquo;s trusted companion&rdquo; (rēʿēh hammelek, literally &ldquo;the king&rsquo;s friend&rdquo;) was a specific court title; in Egyptian administration, &ldquo;Friend of the King&rdquo; was a formal honorific denoting the inner circle of royal confidants.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The final administrative summary positions Joab as military commander alongside the advisory council of Jehoiada and Abiathar. The post-Ahithophel advisory structure (Jehoiada son of Benaiah replacing Ahithophel) reflects the succession of roles that followed the Absalom revolt. Joab&rsquo;s position as army commander (śar haṣṣābāʾ) is the executive branch alongside the king&rsquo;s judicial-advisory cabinet, a bicameral structure of military and civilian administration that mirrors the organization of ancient Near Eastern states where the general and the chancellor operated as parallel powers under the king.</p>"
  },
  "28": {
    "1": "<p>David&rsquo;s final national assembly gathers every category of Israelite leadership: tribal princes, military division commanders, royal estate managers, royal officials, personal guardsmen, and all David&rsquo;s sons &mdash; a complete census of the kingdom&rsquo;s governing apparatus. The comprehensive list recalls Moses&rsquo; final assembly before his death (Deut 31:28) and Joshua&rsquo;s covenant renewal at Shechem (Josh 24:1). David&rsquo;s final address follows the pattern of these great foundational speeches, positioning him as the culmination of the Moses-Joshua-David leadership chain.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David&rsquo;s opening address begins with the disclosure that he had intended to build a permanent house (temple) for the ark, calling it &ldquo;a house of rest for the ark of the covenant of the LORD, a footstool for the feet of our God.&rdquo; The &ldquo;footstool&rdquo; (hăḏōm raglayw) language for the ark or the temple appears in Ps 99:5; 132:7 and connects to the image of YHWH enthroned above the cherubim with the earth as his footstool (Isa 66:1). David&rsquo;s vision was not merely architectural but theological: building a permanent divine dwelling place that would symbolize YHWH&rsquo;s permanent presence with Israel.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The divine prohibition on David building the temple (&ldquo;You are a man of war and have shed blood&rdquo;) reflects the ancient Near Eastern concern for ritual purity in temple-building. In Mesopotamian tradition, temples could only be built by kings who were ritually pure and whose reign was peaceful; building temples after successful warfare required extensive purification rituals. The Chronicler&rsquo;s version of the prohibition differs subtly from Nathan&rsquo;s oracle (ch17): there, YHWH simply deferred the building; here, David explicitly states the blood-guilt reason, adding a theological explanation not present in the earlier account.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David traces YHWH&rsquo;s election: YHWH chose Judah from Israel&rsquo;s tribes, Jesse&rsquo;s house from Judah, and David himself from Jesse&rsquo;s sons. The three-stage election formula (tribe &rarr; family &rarr; individual) mirrors the patriarchal election sequence (Abraham from all nations &rarr; Isaac from Abraham&rsquo;s sons &rarr; Jacob from Isaac&rsquo;s sons). By situating his own election within this pattern, David frames his kingship as the culmination of the entire election history of Israel, and by implication frames Solomon&rsquo;s temple-building as the next stage in that history.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The election of Solomon from &ldquo;all my sons&rdquo; (David had nineteen named sons plus daughters) to sit on &ldquo;the throne of the kingdom of YHWH over Israel&rdquo; is a significant formulation. The kingdom is explicitly identified as YHWH&rsquo;s, not Solomon&rsquo;s: Solomon sits on the divine throne as a regent, not as a sovereign. This theological framing of the Davidic throne as the throne of God became central to messianic interpretation: the king sits where YHWH places him, exercising delegated divine authority over the covenant people.</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s direct oracle to David (&ldquo;God said to me: Solomon your son is the one who will build my house&rdquo;) grounds the Solomon succession in divine appointment rather than merely Davidic preference or political calculation. The adoption formula &ldquo;I have chosen him to be my son, and I will be his father&rdquo; (cf. 17:13) applies to Solomon specifically the covenant language of 2 Sam 7 and Ps 2:7 (&ldquo;You are my son; today I have fathered you&rdquo;). The chosen king is simultaneously the chosen son: the royal and filial categories merge in the Davidic covenant.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The conditional permanence of Solomon&rsquo;s dynasty (&ldquo;I will establish his kingdom forever, if he remains firm&rdquo;) introduces the Mosaic covenant condition into the Davidic promise. The tension between the &ldquo;forever&rdquo; (ʿad ʿôlām) promise and the &ldquo;if&rdquo; (ʾim) condition generated centuries of theological reflection: how can an unconditional promise be conditional? The prophets (Jer 33:17&ndash;21) and the post-exilic community resolved this by distinguishing between the ultimate, unconditional Davidic promise and the conditional blessing of individual Davidic kings &mdash; a resolution that pointed toward the perfect Davidic king who would fulfil the condition completely.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David&rsquo;s command to &ldquo;all Israel, the LORD&rsquo;s assembly&rdquo; (qᵉhal YHWH) to keep the commandments grounds the future success of Solomon&rsquo;s reign in the community&rsquo;s obedience. The qāhāl YHWH (assembly of YHWH) language connects this assembly to the wilderness covenant assembly at Sinai (Deut 4:10; 9:10; 18:16), where YHWH addressed the congregation directly. David is positioning his farewell address within the Sinai covenant framework: just as Moses delivered the commandments to the assembly at Sinai, David delivers the terms of the Davidic covenant to the assembly at Jerusalem.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David&rsquo;s personal charge to Solomon (&ldquo;know the God of your father; serve him with a whole heart and willing soul&rdquo;) is the most concentrated expression of Solomonic spirituality in Chronicles. &ldquo;Know&rdquo; (yāḏaʿ) here means covenantal, relational knowledge, not intellectual knowledge; it is the verb used for intimate relationship (Gen 4:1). The warning that &ldquo;YHWH searches every heart and understands every plan and thought&rdquo; places Solomon under divine omniscience: the king cannot hide his intentions from the God he serves. The choice of &ldquo;seek him&rdquo; or &ldquo;forsake him&rdquo; echoes the Chronicler&rsquo;s darash theology throughout the book.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The concise command &ldquo;Be strong and do it&rdquo; (ḥᵃzaq waʿăśēh) echoes the repeated charge to Joshua (Josh 1:6, 9, 18; Deut 31:7, 23). Solomon&rsquo;s task of building the temple is linguistically assimilated to Joshua&rsquo;s task of conquering the land: both require courage in the face of an overwhelming divine commission that exceeds human ability. The verb ʿāśāh (to do/make) is the primary creation verb; building the sanctuary is a creative act of cosmic significance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>David gives Solomon &ldquo;the plan (tabnît) for everything that had come to him by the Spirit&rdquo; &mdash; the detailed architectural and administrative blueprint for the temple and its operations. The tabnît (plan, pattern, form) is the same word used for the heavenly pattern shown to Moses for the tabernacle (Exod 25:9, 40). Just as Moses received the tabernacle design through divine revelation, David received the temple design through the Spirit; the parallel establishes the temple&rsquo;s divine authorization through a continuous revelatory line from Sinai through the Davidic covenant.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The plan included not only the architectural divisions (courts, rooms, storehouses) but the organizational assignments of priests, Levites, and service personnel &mdash; the entire cultic apparatus. This comprehensive scope (building + personnel + service + utensil weights) parallels the Mosaic instructions where both the tabernacle structure and its service procedures were divinely specified (Exod 25&ndash;31). The temple was not merely a building but a complete liturgical system; both dimensions required divine specification.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The detailed weight specifications for gold and silver articles reflect both the economic realities of ancient temple-building and the theological concern for precision in divine service. Solomon&rsquo;s temple reportedly used 100,000 talents of gold and 1,000,000 talents of silver in its construction (22:14); the precise specifications here ensured that the actual articles matched the divinely-revealed pattern in both material and quantity. Ancient Near Eastern temples maintained detailed inventories of sacred vessels; the Babylonian temple records (preserved in clay tablets) list each sacred utensil with its weight and material composition.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The lampstands (mᵉnōrôt) and their lamps specified in gold and silver follow the Mosaic pattern of the single golden lampstand (Exod 25:31&ndash;40) expanded to ten lampstands for Solomon&rsquo;s temple (1 Kgs 7:49). The weight specification for each lampstand and its lamps ensured consistency and prevented debasement of precious metals. The lampstands symbolized YHWH&rsquo;s presence as light; their precise construction from the specified materials was a theological statement about the quality of worship offered to the divine dwelling.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The tables for the &ldquo;bread of the Presence&rdquo; (leḥem happānîm, literally &ldquo;bread of the face/presence&rdquo;) were the ongoing offering of twelve loaves renewed weekly before YHWH (Lev 24:5&ndash;9). The Mosaic tabernacle had one such table (Exod 25:23&ndash;30); Solomon&rsquo;s temple had ten (1 Kgs 7:48; 2 Chr 4:19). The specification of both gold and silver tables suggests different categories of the presence-bread service, possibly reflecting the expansion from Mosaic singularity to Solomonic multiplicity as the congregation grew.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The precision of weight specifications for the golden service utensils (forks, basins, cups, bowls) reflects the ancient practice of assaying sacred temple vessels to prevent theft through weight reduction. Temple inventories from Mesopotamia and Egypt list each sacred vessel by weight, allowing periodic audits; the specification of &ldquo;weight of each golden bowl&rdquo; and &ldquo;each silver bowl&rdquo; created a permanent reference standard. The basins (mizrāqîm) were used for receiving and tossing the sacrificial blood at the altar.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The &ldquo;golden chariot of the cherubim that spread their wings and covered the ark of the covenant&rdquo; refers to the inner sanctuary&rsquo;s most sacred furnishing: the gold-covered wooden cherubim flanking the ark, whose extended wings created the divine throne-space. The term &ldquo;chariot&rdquo; (merkāḇāh) for the cherub-throne is significant: in Ezekiel 1 and 10, the divine throne is explicitly a four-cherub chariot. The Chronicler&rsquo;s use of merkāḇāh here connects Solomon&rsquo;s temple plan to Ezekiel&rsquo;s vision of the mobile divine throne, suggesting continuity between the First Temple&rsquo;s cherubim and Ezekiel&rsquo;s theophanic vision.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;All this,&rdquo; said David, &ldquo;came to me in writing from the hand of the LORD &mdash; he gave me understanding (hiśkîl) of all the details of the plan.&rdquo; The written divine plan (al-yaḏ YHWH ʿālay) parallels Moses receiving the tabernacle instructions on Sinai: both leaders received divinely-specified architectural plans that they then transmitted to their successors. The verb hiśkîl (gave understanding) uses the same root as the maśkîl psalm titles &mdash; a technical term for skilled, insightful instruction. David&rsquo;s role was not to design the temple but to receive and transmit the divine design.</p>",
    "20": "<p>David&rsquo;s charge to Solomon (&ldquo;Be strong and courageous and do it; do not be afraid or discouraged&rdquo;) uses the exact Joshua-commissioning language (Josh 1:9) discussed at v10. The reason given for confidence is not Solomon&rsquo;s own abilities but divine presence: &ldquo;the LORD God, my God, will be with you. He will not leave you or forsake you.&rdquo; This promise (lōʾ yarpeḵā wᵉlōʾ yaʿazᵇḵā) replicates the Mosaic promise to Joshua (Deut 31:8) and anticipates Hebrews 13:5 where the same assurance is applied to the Christian community.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The final verse of ch28 catalogues the practical resources available to Solomon: organized priestly and Levitical divisions, willing volunteers from all the people, skilled craftsmen in every trade. The phrase &ldquo;every willing person with skill for any service&rdquo; (ḵol nāḏîḇ bᵉḥoḵmāh lᵉḵol ʿăḇōḏāh) uses the vocabulary of the tabernacle-building narrative (Exod 35:10, 25&ndash;26; 36:2&ndash;4): Moses had called on those with skill and willing hearts to build the tabernacle, and David uses the same language to commission the temple workforce. The divine plan, human skill, and willing service converge at the moment of commission.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('context', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRONICLES)
    save_comm('context', '1chronicles', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CHRONICLES.values())
    print(f'1 Chronicles 26-28 context fill: {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
